    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sparks From a Debate, in New York and Beyond</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Jennings letter supports Rick Lazio's attacks on Hillary Clinton with regard to financing of New York Senate campaign</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio and Hillary Clinton Clash on Donations, Taxes and Trust'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>I have to admire Representative Rick A. Lazio. He sincerely buys into campaign reform, and he was right to get in Hillary Rodham Clinton's face over the issue.</p>
        <p>Mrs. Clinton's hypocrisy over soft money highlights the widespread conviction in her party that the rules should apply to everyone but Democrats.</p>
        <p>Did Mr. Lazio cross the line, as some have suggested? I say Mrs. Clinton crossed the line when she decided to use New York as a steppingstone in her quest for power. And her party crossed the line when it decided to back her.</p>
        <p>JOHN JENNINGS  Flushing, Queens, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
